    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Farming Out a Bed</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Christine Dopulos letter comments on Feb 22 article on white elephants that can be part of an inheritance</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As the daughter of parents who filled an enormous Iowa farmhouse with the accumulations of four generations, I read ''Inheriting Memories, With White Elephants'' (Feb. 22) with great enthusiasm. I recently spent $900 to have Aunt Myrtie's 1907 oak wedding bed -- and washstand and sideboard -- sent back to its Midwest roots. My husband and I are delighting in an empty master bedroom, and my brother and sister-in-law are enjoying a perfect match for their 1908 Craftsman house.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As the daughter of parents who filled an enormous Iowa farmhouse with the accumulations of four generations, I read ''Inheriting Memories, With White Elephants'' (Feb. 22) with great enthusiasm. I recently spent $900 to have Aunt Myrtie's 1907 oak wedding bed -- and washstand and sideboard -- sent back to its Midwest roots. My husband and I are delighting in an empty master bedroom, and my brother and sister-in-law are enjoying a perfect match for their 1908 Craftsman house.</p>
        <p>I'm afraid to admit that I would never have been able to sell that bed!</p>
        <p>CHRISTINE DOPULOS  Montclair, N.J.</p>
      </block>
